@NODE Introduction "Introduction"

 @{b}docket (dok'it):@{ub}
   @{i}Any list of things to be done; an agenda.@{ui}

Docket is a useful tool for anyone who wants their Amiga to perform
repetitive tasks at specific times. Docket is aimed at intermediate to
advanced users who want an easier way to schedule tasks to be done on a
regular basis. Docket is most useful if you leave your computer on all the
time and need to perform tasks when you aren't using your Amiga. If you
don't leave your Amiga on all the time, you can still use Docket as long as
you schedule times for when your Amiga is actually on. Docket is not a
reminder/nagging utility.

The idea for Docket came when I was searching for a "cron"-like utility
for the Amiga. There are several flavours of utilities available on
Aminet and most of them are very good. But I found them too complicated
for what I needed with too many bells and whistles. I wanted something
simple to use, resource friendly and powerful enough to do complex tasks.
The solution to my problem is Docket.

If you know a little about the Amiga shell and a little about ARexx, you
too can automate just about anything on your Amiga. See your AmigaOS DOS
and ARexx books for more information about these powerful facilities
available to every Amiga user.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Requirements "Requirements"

Requires AmigaOS 4.0 or higher.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Usage "Using Docket"

@{b}Starting Docket@{ub}

Docket is implemented as a commodity and follows the rules as for any other
standard commodity. Docket can be started from either the Shell or the
Workbench.

If starting from the Shell, the following command template is used:
 CX_PRIORITY/K/N, CX_POPKEY/K, CX_POPUP/K

If starting from the Workbench, the following tool types are available:
 CX_PRIORITY
 CX_POPKEY
 CX_POPUP

For an explanation of the above commodities options, see your
"AmigaOS: Workbench" manual in the "Commodities Drawer" section.

By default Docket will not display its graphical user interface (GUI).
Docket is designed to run silently in the background. The GUI can be opened
by starting Docket twice, using the option CX_POPUP=YES or by using
Exchange's "Show Interface" button.


@{b}Stopping Docket@{ub}

Docket can be either deactivated or quit at any time.

To deactivate Docket use Exchange and select "Inactive". When Docket is
deactivated it will not execute item commands when they expire.

To quit Docket select "Quit" from the menu, select "Remove" using Exchange
or send the Docket process a CTRL-C signal.


@{b}Docket's GUI@{ub}

The GUI was designed to be very intuitive and should not require very much
explanation. There are two basic editor windows available. One is the
Docket editor itself which displays the list of items. The second editor is
the item editor which edits a single item.

One thing that is not so obvious is the "Save" feature. Docket will not
automatically save your docket and you will have to explicity choose "Save"
from the docket menu. Your docket will be loaded and saved to the file
"ENVARC:docket.prefs" to keep things simple.

Be sure to test your commands and/or scripts before creating a docket item
for them. Docket will not inform you if a command failed to execute. There
is a test button to try your command from the item editor as well.

The GUI is not very forgiving. There are no "Are you sure?" requesters or
a whole lot of error messages. I'll consider adding that kind of
functionality if someone asks @{"me" LINK Author} to...


@{b}End of the Month@{ub}

The end of the month is handled in a human logical manner. For example, if
you have created a monthly item which expires on day 31 of each month, the
item will expire on the last day of each month. This made the most sense
because monthly items should be executed every month and not just those
months which happen to have 31 days in them. Leap years are handled
automatically and February will have the correct number of days in it.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Bugs "Known Bugs"

The following bugs are known to exist:

 · There are two cases where docket items can become "stale" and never
   execute. One case is when the system time is moved forward and
   backward so that an item is caught between a later time and a sooner
   time. The second case is when the docket is inactive and an item should
   expire.

@ENDNODE


